anguage and Intercultural Citizenship Education for a Culture of Peace: The Malvinas/Falklands Project -- t10. Human Rights Education in Language Teaching -- tReflections: Learning from the Challenges and Seeking Ways Forward -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe contributors to this volume have collaborated to present their work on introducing competences in intercultural communication and citizenship into foreign language education. The book examines how learners and teachers think about citizenship and interculturality, and shows how teachers and researchers from primary to university education can work together across continents to develop new curricula and pedagogy. This involves the creation of a new theory of intercultural citizenship and a procedure for implementation. The book is written by teacher researchers who aim to help other teachers, and concludes with reflections on the lessons they have learnt which will help others to implement these ideas in their own practice. The book is essential reading for foreign language educators and researchers, students in pre-service teacher training and teachers in in-service training.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aIntercultural communication. 0aInternational education. 0aLanguages, ModernxStudy and teaching. 0aMulticultural education. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Study & Teaching.2bisacsh  aCitizenship education.  aCurriculum design.  aEducation for intercultural citizenship.  aForeign language education.  aIntercultural citizenship.  aIntercultural competence.  aInterculturality.  aTeacher collaboration.  aTelecollaboration in foreign language education.1 aArcuri, María Emilia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarr